&lt;h2>Watch for&lt;span class="hx:absolute hx:-mt-20" id="watch-for">&lt;/span>
&lt;a href="#watch-for" class="subheading-anchor" aria-label="Permalink for this section">&lt;/a>&lt;/h2>&lt;ul>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>&lt;code>Object.assign&lt;/code> mistaken for the unsafe pattern.&lt;/strong> It
isn&amp;rsquo;t — &lt;code>Object.assign&lt;/code> does shallow assignment and ignores
&lt;code>__proto__&lt;/code> as a key (it&amp;rsquo;s a getter, not a writable
property on plain objects). The audit should keep it.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>&lt;code>qs.parse&lt;/code> with &lt;code>allowPrototypes: true&lt;/code>.&lt;/strong> Some legacy
Express apps set this. Remove.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>&lt;code>Object.create(null)&lt;/code> breaking libraries that expect
&lt;code>.hasOwnProperty&lt;/code>.&lt;/strong> Use &lt;code>Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty.call(obj, k)&lt;/code>
instead.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>GraphQL variables.&lt;/strong> Mapping untyped GraphQL variables
into nested option objects is a common entry-point.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>&lt;strong>TypeScript doesn&amp;rsquo;t save you.&lt;/strong> A type assertion on a
parsed JSON payload is not a runtime check. The boundary
filter is.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
